1 The Challenger Data

The Challenger formed the main backbone of investigation of the disaster where NASA’s space shuttle named “Challenger” crashed a few minutes after its launch on 28 January, 1986. The Presidential Commission’s report outlined that the cause of the incident was mainly the failure of an device called “O-Rings” which sealed a joint in the booster rockets. It was also mentioned that the failure was perhaps due to extreme low temperature which in turn affected the rings creating a leak of combustion gases. The Challenger data set contains data on number of accidents related to “O-Rings”, and some other potential variables (e.g. pressure and temperature during the time of launch) from \(23\) pre-accidental space shuttles. We present the data below:-

challenger<-read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/egarpor/handy/master/datasets/challenger.txt", sep="", header = TRUE)
challenger

We note that here we are given data mainly for the primary “O-Rings” and they are used to seal both nozzle joints and field joints. The incidents happening due to failure of rings in filed joints are given importance in the description of case study. So, our analysis will not work with those incidents. Variables nfails.field,nfails.nozzle denote the exact number of failures where as fail.field and fail.nozzle are just indicator variables denoting \(1\) if there was at least one incident, or else \(0\).

2 Towards choosing a Bayesian model

In bayesian theory we always try to quantify our uncertainty about the values of the fixed parameters by taking a prior distribution based on our apriori belief which when combined with the likelihood of the observations results in the updated posterior information about the parameters. In our problem, we are going to consider fail.field as our response variable. The \(i^{th}\) response \(y_i\) (\(i=1,2, \dots 23\) in our case) can be considered as observation from a Bernoulli distribution with success probability \(p_i\). A logistic regression model uses the logit link to relate log odds of success to a linear combination of predictors. Since in our case, the only predictor is temperature (let denote \(t_i\)) so we have a following model \[\log\left(\frac{p_i}{1-p_i}\right)=a+b*t_i \quad \quad i=1,2, \dots 23\]. The likelihood is \(l(a,b|data) = \frac{\exp(a\sum_{i=1}^{23} y_i+b\sum_{i=1}^{23} t_iy_i)}{\Pi_{i=1}^{23}(1+exp(a+bt_i))}\). If our uncertainty about parameter \((a,b)\) is quantified by prior distribution \(\pi(a,b)\) then our posterior is \(\pi(a,b|data) \propto \pi(a,b)\frac{\exp(a\sum_{i=1}^{23} y_i+b\sum_{i=1}^{23} t_iy_i)}{\Pi_{i=1}^{23}(1+exp(a+bt_i))}\). Choosing a prior one of the concerns in bayesian analysis. There are some methods which help us to choose prior based on optimizing information criteria or based on some frequentist ideas etc. However, for simplicity we will be working with flat uniform prior on \((a,b)\) over \(\mathbb{R} \times \mathbb{R}\). In otherwords, \(\pi(a,b) \propto 1, \quad \forall (a,b) \in \mathbb{R} \times \mathbb{R}\). Now, under such a prior our posterior becomes proportional to the likelihood \(l(a,b|data)\). However, this posterior does not seem to be tractable enough to allow us to draw samples directly from it. So, we would take resort to Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) techniques to draw samples from this posterior.

3 MCMC-MH Algorithm

3.1 Choice of Prior and Proposal

In our case, we will use Metropolis-Hastings(M-H) algorithms. For that we need to propose a density \(q(.|(a_k,b_k))\) which will help us to draw a bivariate markov chain \((a_n,b_n)\) using M-H algorithm. The density should be such that we can take samples from it easily. As long as the proposal density has some nice properties the markov chain should have the asymptotic stationary distribution as the posterior density. In our case we will consider proposal which would not depend on the current state of the chain \((a_k,b_k)\), i.e. \(q(.|(a_k,b_k))=q() \quad \forall (a_k,b_k)\). Thus, it means that we will be employing an independence sampler. There is a reason behind taking independence sampler. If our chosen is such that $ k (a,b) $, \(k\) being positive and not depending on data, then by Example \(1\) of Jones & Hobert[1], the generated markov chain will be uniformly ergodic, which is even stronger than geometric ergodicity which happens when the distance between the markov transition kernel and target posterior reduces geometrically. So, we can expect faster convergence of our chain. Now, to search for a proposal which satisfy the uniform boundedness condition we restricted our attention only to those densities which has more or less same shape with our posterior. Let us see the shape of our posterior in a range consisting of mle’s of the parameter. By mle’s we mean the estimates of \(a\) and \(b\) which we obtain by frequentist logistic regression and it appears to be \(a=7.583\) and \(b=-0.417\).

logis<-glm(fail.field~ temp, data=challenger, family="binomial")

target<-function(a,b){
  
  m<-mean(challenger[,5])
  n<-mean(  challenger[,5] *challenger[,7] )
  a1<-exp(a*23*m+ b*23*n)
s<-rep(0,23)
for(i in 1:23)  
{
  s[i]<-1+exp(a+b*challenger[,7][i])

q=prod(s)
i<-a1/q

  return(i)

  
}

When compared with the posterior surface we can see that it has similar kind of shape (not exactly same though). We guess taking such a proposal which matches with target distribution upto at least certain extent would help us.

As we will see below, this proposal also satisfies the condition mentioned in Jones Hobert[1]. For this we consider \(\log\left(\frac{\pi(.|data)}{q(.)}\right)=\log(\pi(.|data))-\log(q(.))\) and try to see if it attains maximum over a bounded support.Then we will see if the maximum changes if the support range is gradually increased. Because of computational complexity of large numbers by R we will perform the task for three different ranges viz.:- (1) \((-100,100) \times (-10,10)\), (2) \((-150,150) \times (-15,15)\), and (3)\((-200,200) \times (-20,20)\).

lcauchy<-function(a,b){
  return(log(bcauchy(a,b)))
}

ltarget<-function(a,b){
  
  m<-mean(challenger[,5])
  n<-mean(  challenger[,5] *challenger[,7] )
  a1<-a*23*m+ b*23*n
  s<-rep(0,23)
  for(i in 1:23)  
  {
    s[i]<-log(1+exp(a+b*challenger[,7][i]))
  }
  q=sum(s)
  i<-a1-q
  
  return(i)
  
  
}

x<-seq(-100,100, by=1)
y<-seq(-10,10, by= 0.1)
z<-matrix(0, nrow=length(x), ncol=length(y))


for(i in 1:length(x)){
  for( j in 1:length(y)){
    z[i,j]<-ltarget(x[i], y[j])-lcauchy(x[i], y[j])
    
  }
  
}


max(z)
## [1] -5.941494

3.2 Generation of Markov Chain

To draw samples using the flat prior and the proposed proposal density, we now form our corresponding R functions which would run the algorithm.

rbcauchy<-function(){
  return(   rmvc(n=1, c(7.584, -0.417), matrix(c(20, 0, 0, 0.01), nrow=2, ncol=2)        ))
}

## acceptance probability

accept1<-function(x,y){
  q1<-ltarget(x[1], x[2])
  q2<-ltarget(y[1],y[2])
  
    q<-(q2-q1)+log(( bcauchy(x[1],x[2])/bcauchy(y[1],y[2])    ))
  
  
  if (q<=0){
    return(exp(q))
  }
  else{
    return(1)
  }
}

metropolis1<-function(initial, k){
  s<-list()
  s[[1]]<-c(0,0)
  for(i in 2:k) {
    
    s[[i]]<-s[[(i-1)]]
    
  }
  
  s[[1]]<-initial
  
  for(i in 2:k){
    
    
    
      al<- rbcauchy()
    
    al<- as.vector(al)
    pl<-  accept1(s[[i-1]], al) 
    
    pll<-sample(c(1:2), 1, prob=c(pl, 1-pl))
    
    if(pll==1){
      s[[i]]<-al
    }
    
    else{
      s[[i]]<-s[[i-1]]
    }
    
  } 
  
  
  return(s)
  
}

The function metropolis1 returns a list of \(k\) many samples drawn by M-H algorithm for a initial value of \((a,b)\). We take the mle’s as our initial values and we generate 50000 samples. A sample of \(20\) samples are shown below.Each row denote a sample.

set.seed(34)

The histogram of \(a\) values appear to be a positively skewed distribution, whereas that of \(b\) values appears as heavily negatively skewed one.

We can get the estimates of \(a\) and \(b\) by taking mean of this posterior samples.

s1<-mean(a)
s2<-mean(b)

Now, we can find the standard error of these posterior estimates by using method of batch means as mentioned in Jones & Hobert[1]. Let us take batches of size \(5000\) to get \(10\) samples of \(S_k^a=\frac{1}{5000} \sum_{i=5000(k-1)}^{5000k-1}a_i\). Then we can use the formula mentioned in the paper. Similar formula can be applied for \(b\) values too.

m1<-rep(0,10)
m2<-rep(0,10)
for(i in 1:10){
  w<-5000*(i-1)+1
  e<-(5000*i)
 m1[i]<-(1/5000)* sum(a[w:e])
 m2[i] <-(1/5000)* sum(b[w:e])
  
}

sqrt(5000*var(m1))
## [1] 31.03624
sqrt(5000*var(m2))
## [1] 1.472421

So we see that the estimates of standard errors are high. And, it perhaps tells us that we should have generated even more samples so that we could have taken more higher batch size. This might happen because we are not considering any burn-in in our case as it often termed as unnecessary (as mentioned in http://users.stat.umn.edu/~geyer/mcmc/burn.html)

4 On Convergence Diagnostics

Let us see the time series plot for both the \(a\) sample vales and \(b\) sample values.

plot(1:50000, a, type="l")

plot(1:50000,b, type="l")

It can be seen that they more or less look like a “black hair caterpillar”. So it seems like that the chain does not get stuck in some part of the parameter space, and explores the parameter space fully. This indicates a well converging pattern.

Secondly, we consider the sample auto-covariance function versus lags plot of both the quantities. A good chain should show a decreasing pattern.

library(coda)
autocorr.plot(a)

autocorr.plot(b)

Since the plots shows a decreasing pattern we can say that as iteration is increasing the samples’ correlation is reducing and they would eventually behave as i.i.d.

We can also test the convergence formally by Geweke’s convergence diagnostic. This test is based on test of equality of means of first part (\(10\) percent) and last part (\(50\) percent of the data). If the samples are drawn from stationary distribution the two means are equal and Geweke’s statistic has an asymptotically standard normal distribution. The function geweke.diag from coda package would give use the value of test statistic (a standard \(z\) score) for each parameter separately.

library(coda)
M1<-as.mcmc(M)
geweke.diag(M1, frac1=0.1, frac2=0.5)
## 
## Fraction in 1st window = 0.1
## Fraction in 2nd window = 0.5 
## 
##    var1    var2 
## -0.4520  0.4146

Normally if observed \(z\) values lie in the range \(\{z:|z|>1.96\}\), then it becomes problematic. But in our case it turns out there is no problem.

5 Posterior Inference

The negative skewness of the histogram of the \(b\) values is clearly showing that \(b\), the coefficient of temperature in the true model is very likely to assume a negative value. It indicates a negative dependence on the temperature. Secondly, we already know that “Challenger” crashed at \(-0.6\) degree celcius. So, putting \(t_i=-0.6\) in our logistic regression model we have \(p_i=\frac{\exp(a-0.6b)}{1+\exp(a-0.6b)}\). Given that we now have a well behaved sample from posterior distribution of \((a,b)\), we can try to find out the histogram of this quantity \(p_i\).

ps<-function(x){
  c<-exp(x[1]-(0.6*x[2]))
  return(c/(1+c))
}
pi<-apply(M,1, ps)


data<-as.data.frame(pi)
p1<-ggplot(data) +
    geom_histogram(aes(x = pi, y = ..density..),
                   binwidth =0.02, fill = "grey", color = "black")
p1

So, we can see that this appears distribution with negative skew and mainly concentrated around 1. So, the posterior probability that “Challenger” would face at least one failure due to “O-Rings” was very high given the data and temperature \(-0.6\) degree celcius.  We can also do one thing. We can generate similar kind of histograms under different temperatures and can find the distribution of posterior probability.

ps<-function(x){
  c<-exp(x[1]+(5*x[2]))
  return(c/(1+c))

So, as we can see that when temperature gradually increases the distribution of posterior probability become more sparsed in \((0,1)\) and at \(20\) degree celcius it becomes really well dispersed. At \(15\) degree celcius the posterior estimates of mean becomes So, reiterating in the same way as Dalal et al.[2] did, we say that a postponement in the launch of “Challenger” to a higher temperature would have perhaps lowered the risk of catching a disaster.
